    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>In ''A Few Good Lawyers'' (Op-Ed, April 16), David M. Schizer has taken the wrong approach to improve tax collection.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>In ''A Few Good Lawyers'' (Op-Ed, April 16), David M. Schizer has taken the wrong approach to improve tax collection.</p>
        <p>Rather than more and better lawyers, the thrust should be to radically overhaul and simplify our income tax laws so that everyone pays a fair share and lawyers and C.P.A.'s are not required to either calculate taxes or devise schemes to avoid them.</p>
        <p>It is the complexity of our current tax laws, not the lack of lawyers, that results in questionable tax avoidance schemes.</p>
        <p>Thomas W. Turner  Bellevue, Neb., April 16, 2007</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
